      <abstract>
        <label>Abstract</label>
        <p>Males of some groups of bees have to find a place outside the nests to sleep, sometimes forming “male sleeping aggregations”. Here we report the first record of “dense” male sleeping aggregation of two different genera of <tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="tribe">Eucerini</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name> bees observed in Bahia, Brazil. We discuss the possible aim of this kind of aggregation as well the plant utilized on aggregate.</p>
      </abstract>
